---
import Base from '../../layouts/Base.astro';
import SectionHeader from '../../components/SectionHeader.astro';
import PullQuote from '../../components/PullQuote.astro';
import Annotation from '../../components/Annotation.astro';
---
<Base title="The Chatbot Won't Save You" section={7}>
  <SectionHeader n={7} title="The Chatbot Won't Save You" meta="~500w" />

  <div class="prose">

    <p>
      The story goes like this: dashboards are hard to use because you need to know
      where to look. Natural language BI solves this. Ask any question in plain English,
      get an instant answer. No SQL, no training required. Data democratised.
    </p>

    <p>
      The story is wrong, and it is worth being precise about why.
    </p>

    <p>
      Natural language BI does lower the technical barrier to querying data. This is real.
      A product manager who could not write a SQL join can now ask "what's our weekly
      retention by acquisition channel" and get a table. That used to require an analyst.
      This is genuinely useful for a narrow class of queries from a specific kind of user.
    </p>

    <p>
      But the premise of the democratisation argument is that the barrier to insight was
      technical. That if only non-technical people could query data directly, they would
      ask the right questions and make better decisions. This was never true.
      The barrier to insight is not syntax. It is knowing what to ask.
    </p>

    <PullQuote>
      <p>Democratising bad analysis isn't progress. The query shapes the insight —
      and most people don't know what to query.</p>
    </PullQuote>

    <p>
      Knowing what to ask requires knowing what question is actually worth answering.
      It requires understanding the data model well enough to know which questions are
      answerable and which are misleading traps. It requires knowing that "conversion rate"
      can be calculated seventeen different ways and that the one the chatbot picks
      might not be the one you meant. It requires knowing when an answer is surprising
      because something real changed and when it is surprising because the query was
      subtly wrong.
    </p>

    <p>
      None of these requirements go away because the interface is conversational.
      If anything, the natural language interface makes them worse, because it creates
      the impression that the answer is authoritative. A SQL query surfaces its own
      assumptions — you can read it, scrutinise it, ask whether the join is right.
      A plain-English answer from a BI chatbot has no such affordance. It just sounds
      confident.
    </p>

    <Annotation label="The compounding problem">
      Bad queries compound. A non-technical user who gets an answer they don't understand
      will not scrutinise the underlying query. They will either trust it or not ask again.
      Both outcomes are worse than having an analyst involved. The analyst at least knows
      when something is off.
    </Annotation>

    <p>
      There is also the query shapes the insight problem. The questions people think to ask
      are constrained by their mental model of the business. If you believe that acquisition
      cost is the most important lever, you will ask questions about acquisition cost.
      You will not ask about the downstream quality of the users you acquire, because that
      is not the shape of the question that occurs to you. The chatbot will dutifully answer
      the question you asked and say nothing about the question you did not ask.
    </p>

    <p>
      This was always true of dashboards too — you only see what you built panels for.
      But dashboards at least force some upfront deliberation about which questions matter.
      The chatbot's infinite query flexibility can actually be worse: it allows you to
      pursue whatever question surfaces in the moment, which is often the wrong one.
    </p>

    <p>
      The right use of natural language BI is narrow. It is useful for ad-hoc exploration
      by people who already understand the data and need a faster interface to it.
      It is useful for lowering the friction on specific known-useful queries. It is not
      useful as a substitute for thinking carefully about which questions your organisation
      actually needs to answer.
    </p>

    <p>
      The root problem, as in every era, is the same: most organisations do not know
      what question they are actually trying to answer. A better interface does not
      fix that. It just makes it faster to ask the wrong question.
    </p>

  </div>
</Base>
